{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480622"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:48:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"87"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"87","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/87"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.22,0.01,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"87"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41351"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"87","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/87"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"87"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26107"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"4100"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12929"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42965"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41351"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman attends for the results of her recently performed cervical screening test (CST). Her previous test was normal. She is currently asymptomatic and presented due to the 5-year recall for the CST. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe results are positive for HPV (not 16/18), and reflex LBC (liquid based cytology) shows a possible LSIL (low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan for this woman\u0027s ongoing care?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat co-test now","Repeat LBC in 6 weeks","Colposcopy","Repeat cervical screening test in 3 years","Repeat HPV test in 12 months"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has tested positive for HPV (not 16/18) and a reflex liquid based cytology (LBC) has been performed. When oncogenic HPV is detected, cytology will be performed on the same cervical sample and this is known as reflex liquid-based cytology. Reflex LBC occurs if the HPV test is positive whereas if the HPV is negative, all testing is deemed complete and the patient given a \u0027low risk\u0027 result with need for repeat testing in 5 years. Reflex LBC for this patient reported possible low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (pLSIL), and therefore a result of \u0027intermediate risk\u0027 is reported. Hence a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat HPV test in 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate course of action. A reflex LBC will occur if this repeat test is positive for HPV. Approximately 70% of HPV (non 16/18) infections will clear within 12 months. If the subsequent Co-test was negative, then the patient could return to routine 5 yearly screening. If on the third repeat test, HPV is still detected, then referral for colposcopy is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to identify if the woman is symptomatic and determine risk factors such as smoking or immunodeficiency, as if she was experiencing symptoms such as post-coital bleeding this would NOT be a screening test (HPV test and reflex LBC) and the co-test (HPV test and LBC) would be required. Symptomatic women should be tested anytime and should not wait for routine screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERefer to the reference below for the cervical screening pathway flow chart.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Currently in Australia, a cervical screening test should be offered to all women from age 25 and then every 5 years.","A CST is performed for screening (HPV with reflex LBC), where as a co-test is performed for symptomatic women (HPV and LBC).","HPV 16/18 have been identified as being the most oncogenic strains of the HPV virus and require closer follow up than HPV non-16/18."],"references":["Cancer Council Australia, Cervical Cancer Screening Guidelines [2016]. https://wiki.cancer.org.au/australia/Guidelines:Cervical_cancer/Screening. Accessed 26/11/2021","Roeske, L, GPs\u0027 guide to completing a cervical screening pathology request form. [2018]. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/newsgp/gp-opinion/guide-to-completing-cervical-screening-pathology-r.","Cervical Screening Pathway Flow chart. https://wiki.cancer.org.au/australiawiki/images/4/4b/Flowchart_6_1_NEW.pdf. Accessed 26/11/2021"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26107"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"87"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26107"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-11T08:36:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-11T08:36:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"87"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41351"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66",